C++ SOLUTION:
class Solution {
public:
    ListNode* deleteDuplicates(ListNode* head) {
        if (head == nullptr) return head;
        
        ListNode dummy(0);
        ListNode* curr = &dummy;
        ListNode* temp = head;
        
        while (temp != NULL) {
            // We only add the node to our new list if it's the LAST node of its kind.
            // This happens if it's the very last node in the list (temp->next == NULL)
            // OR if its value is different from the next node's value.
            if (temp->next == NULL || temp->val != temp->next->val) {
                curr->next = temp;  // Link the actual node, not its integer value
                curr = curr->next;  // Move our builder pointer forward
            }
            
            temp = temp->next;      // Always move temp forward
        }
        
        // CRITICAL: We must cut off the end of our new list! 
        // Otherwise, it might still be pointing to trailing duplicates.
        curr->next = NULL;
        
        // Return dummy.next because dummy itself is just our starting placeholder
        return dummy.next; 
    }
};

EXPLAINATION:
Example 1 from your screen: head = [1, 1, 2].

To make it easier to track, let's call the first one 1(a) and the second one 1(b).

The Setup
Before the loop starts, here is where our pointers are:

dummy is a fake starting node with value 0.

curr points to dummy. We will use curr to build our new, clean list.

temp points to the start of the original list: 1(a) -> 1(b) -> 2.

Step-by-Step Execution
Iteration 1: temp is at 1(a)

The Check: The code asks, "Is temp the last node (temp->next == NULL) OR is its value different from the next node (1 != 1)?"

The Result: Both are False. Because the current value (1) matches the next value (1), we know this is a duplicate. We don't want to keep it.

Action: The if block is skipped. temp simply moves forward to 1(b).

Current New List: dummy(0)

Iteration 2: temp is at 1(b)

The Check: The code asks, "Is temp the last node OR is its value different from the next node (1 != 2)?"

The Result: True! Because 1 is not equal to 2, we know this 1(b) is the very last 1 in the duplicate group. This is the one we want to keep.

Action: * curr->next = temp; (We link our new list to 1(b)).

curr = curr->next; (We move our builder pointer forward to sit on 1(b)).

temp = temp->next; (temp moves forward to 2).

Current New List: dummy(0) -> 1(b)

Iteration 3: temp is at 2

The Check: The code asks, "Is temp the last node (temp->next == NULL) OR is its value different from the next node?"

The Result: True! Because 2 is the very last node in the list, temp->next is NULL.

Action:

curr->next = temp; (We link our new list to 2).

curr = curr->next; (We move our builder pointer forward to sit on 2).

temp = temp->next; (temp moves forward to NULL).

Current New List: dummy(0) -> 1(b) -> 2

The Cleanup
Now that temp is NULL, the while loop finishes.

curr->next = NULL; We execute this critical step. Since curr is currently sitting on 2, this explicitly tells the computer, "The list ends here." (If we didn't do this, and our original list was [1, 2, 2], the 2 we kept might still be secretly pointing to the discarded duplicate 2).

return dummy.next;
We return the node immediately after our fake starting point. dummy.next points to 1(b), so the computer receives 1 -> 2, which is the correct answer!
